  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite limited citations and community discourse, \"Images of Immigrants and Refugees\" offers valuable insights into the portrayal of immigration and refugee issues, showcasing a significant link to sustainability policy through its thematic exploration.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in 2019 by Leuven University Press, \"Images of Immigrants and Refugees\" engages critically with the visual narratives surrounding immigration and refugees. Although the publication has not garnered citations or online mentions, its exploration of sustainability and policy relevance indicates its potential importance in discussions on these critical contemporary issues.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The inferred role of commercial linkage, with a strength rating of 0.9, demonstrates that the book is accessible via platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads, suggesting a pathway for broader public engagement with its themes. This commercial availability may facilitate interest beyond academic circles, thus inviting various audiences to explore its content.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Furthermore, the publication's connection to sustainability and policy relevance is significant, with a strength of 0.55 inferred from its alignment with the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). This aspect underscores the work's relevance in contributing to discourse surrounding sustainable refugee policies and the societal implications of immigration.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In conclusion, while \"Images of Immigrants and Refugees\" may currently lack extensive academic uptake and public discourse, it is positioned within a relevant and critical framework of sustainability and policy, indicating its potential for future impact in these key areas. The book serves as a significant output that responds to pressing global issues, even as it navigates the complexities of visibility and engagement in both scholarly and public spheres.</p>",
